00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:07.070 --> 00:00:09.640
&gt;&gt; The Library of Congress
has assembled a wealth

00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:13.350
of primary sources
for the K-12 educator.

00:00:13.350 --> 00:00:17.850
One great place to start is
on the Teachers Page.The staff

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:21.650
of the Library has done much of
the work of finding primary sources

00:00:21.650 --> 00:00:25.400
for you, and has created
a number of short cuts

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:29.300
for finding primary
sources without searching.

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:33.560
Most teachers find that the Primary
Source Sets offer easy access

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:37.850
to selected primary sources
that they can use quickly.

00:00:37.850 --> 00:00:42.020
A Primary Source Set is a set
of selected primary sources

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:48.010
on a specific topic most of which
are available as easy-to-use PDFs.

00:00:48.010 --> 00:00:52.890
Each set also come with historical
background information on its topic

00:00:52.890 --> 00:00:57.800
as well as teaching ideas and
tools to guide student analysis.

00:00:57.800 --> 00:01:01.590
Primary Sources by State takes
a close-up look at the states

00:01:01.590 --> 00:01:04.740
by presenting selected
primary sources for each

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:10.270 position:56%
of the fifty states, the District of
Columbia and the U.S. territories.

00:01:10.270 --> 00:01:14.220
These state sets include primary
sources from different eras

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:19.140 position:56%
of each state's history, and usually
feature a wide range of formats,

00:01:19.140 --> 00:01:24.410
from manuscripts and maps
to films and folk songs.

00:01:24.410 --> 00:01:27.080
Another way to find
primary sources is

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:29.970 position:56%
to use the Today in History feature.

00:01:29.970 --> 00:01:34.400
Today in History is available
from the Library's home page.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:38.410
Today in History features
information and primary sources

00:01:38.410 --> 00:01:43.240
on a specific event or events in
history, along with suggestions

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:47.870
for how to search for additional
primary sources on the topic.

00:01:47.870 --> 00:01:50.490
In addition, you can
use the archives link

00:01:50.490 --> 00:01:55.500
to search all 365 entries for
Today in History or search

00:01:55.500 --> 00:01:59.470
for specific topics by keyword.

00:01:59.470 --> 00:02:02.300
The Library's experts
are also available

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:04.960
through the Ask a Librarian service

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:08.820
if searching doesn't yield
the primary sources you need.

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:11.130
Look for the Ask a Librarian button

00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:14.730
on each Library of
Congress Web page.

00:02:16.210 --> 00:02:19.870
&gt;&gt; This has been a presentation
of the Library of Congress.

00:02:19.870 --> 00:02:22.220
Visit us at loc.gov.

